1 The Problem — Administered Trust and Cascading
Surveillance
1.1 The Administered Identity Graph
Contemporary digital systems rest upon a model of trust that is fundamentally administrative. Every
interaction — from a user logging in to an API exchanging tokens — passes through a chain of
credential checks managed by centralized authorities. Certificate Authority hierarchies issue TLS
certificates, OAuth providers grant access tokens, and API keys serve as identity proxies. Each of
these instruments links a computational action to a person or an organization through an
administrative decision made at some prior moment. The trust is not intrinsic to the transaction; it is
delegated from above.
This delegation creates the administered identity graph: a web of relationships where identifiers —
email addresses, device IDs, session tokens, mobile advertising identifiers (MAIDs) — are stitched
together by entities whose economic incentive is to maximize the density and reach of that graph. The
graph itself becomes a surveillance instrument. When a single advertising SDK can bridge a user's
mobile device identifier to their desktop cookie and their connected-TV signature, the identity graph
is no longer a trust infrastructure — it is an attack surface.1
The fundamental vulnerability is structural, not operational. Trust granted by an authority can be
revoked by that authority, compromised by that authority, or — most critically — sold by that
authority. The question is not whether administered trust can be improved with better policies; the
