1.2 The Surveillance Stack as Threat Model
To frame the architectural requirements precisely, we present an explicit four-layer threat model
derived from the current state of ambient digital surveillance. Each layer is independently
documented in the research literature; taken together, they form a cascading system in which
blocking any single layer merely redirects tracking through another. The result is a Hamiltonian Drift
problem: the surveillance system optimizes around any local constraint.
Layer 0: Radio (BLE / Wi-Fi Telemetry)
Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) advertising packets constitute a form of ambient telemetry that operates
below the application layer. Every smartphone, wearable, and IoT device continuously broadcasts BLE
advertisements containing service UUIDs, manufacturer data, and transmission metadata. While MAC
address randomization was introduced as a privacy countermeasure, research has conclusively
demonstrated that it provides only cosmetic protection. Higher-layer payloads carry stable
correlation handles that persist across MAC rotations, enabling device tracking through temporal and
spatial fingerprinting techniques.1
Academic work on BLE fingerprinting has shown that physical-layer imperfections in radio
transmitters — unique to each chipset — create device signatures that survive all software-level
randomization attempts.2 Complementary research at the University at Albany's Scholars Archive has
further documented how BLE advertising metadata, including timing patterns and payload structure,
can be used to re-identify devices with high accuracy even when MAC addresses rotate as specified
by the Bluetooth Core standard.14 Wi-Fi probe requests present an analogous attack surface: despite
randomization in modern operating systems, the sequence and timing of probe requests, combined
with information element fingerprinting, allow passive observers to construct persistent device
identifiers.14
The implication for trust architecture is direct: any system that relies on device-level identity —
including device attestation schemes and hardware-bound credentials — inherits this radio-layer
attack surface. The device is identifiable before the application stack even loads.
Layer 1: Application (SDK Supply Chain)
At the application layer, the surveillance infrastructure is embedded directly into the software supply
chain through Software Development Kits (SDKs). Research published in Big Data & Society documents
what the authors term "Super SDKs" — Google's mobile development libraries are present in over 93%
of Android applications, creating a monoculture of surveillance infrastructure that developers
integrate not by choice but by necessity.3 These SDKs perform "ID bridging" — the technical process
of linking Mobile Advertising Identifiers (MAIDs) to desktop browser cookies, connected-TV identifiers,
and other cross-device signals — thereby constructing the raw material for identity graphs.
The economic model underlying this infrastructure is what we term Surveillance-as-Infrastructure
(SaaI): developers receive free analytics, crash reporting, push notification, and authentication
