4 Provenance Chain — Content-Addressable Integrity
4.1 IPFS/Filecoin Anchoring via Storacha
The TAS provenance architecture rests on the InterPlanetary File System (IPFS) and its incentivized
persistence layer, Filecoin, accessed through the Storacha gateway. IPFS provides
content-addressable storage: every piece of content is identified by its Content Identifier (CID), a
cryptographic hash of the content itself. The same content always produces the same CID regardless
of where or when it is stored, and any modification — however small — produces a completely
different CID.6
Filecoin extends IPFS with economic guarantees through two complementary proof systems.
Proof-of-Replication (PoRep) requires each storage provider to prove that they are storing a
physically unique copy of the data — not merely pointing to someone else's copy. Proof-of-Spacetime
(PoSt) requires ongoing proof that the data is stored continuously over time, not merely present at
verification checkpoints.7 Together, these proofs create a verifiable persistence guarantee: content
identified by a CID is not merely addressable but provably stored with physical redundancy across
time. Storacha provides the operational interface to this stack, managing the complexity of Filecoin
deal-making and proof verification while exposing a developer-friendly API.8
4.2 The TAS Provenance Stack
The TAS provenance chain is a multi-layer attestation system where each layer echoes the integrity of
the one below. The stack proceeds as follows: Git commits serve as the first-layer attestation,
providing cryptographic proof of what code existed at what time. TAS-DNA metadata chaining
