The distinction between recognition and re-cognition is central to understanding the TAS trust
architecture. Recognition, in the conventional computational sense, is pattern matching against stored
templates: a facial recognition system compares an input image against a database of known faces; a
credential verification system compares a presented token against a registry of valid tokens.
Recognition is passive — it consumes inputs and produces boolean outputs.
Re-Cognition, as defined within TAS, is fundamentally different. It is the recursive awareness of one's
own cognitive process — the capacity of a computational system to verify its own integrity through
